For present purposes the detailed structure of these equations and inequalities is not needed.

Now recall our discussion in SectionÂ 2 of the difference in viewpoints between the study of Goursat distributions and the study of curvilinear data. From the former perspective, one cannot distinguish, at level 222, between regular and vertical data. Thus in the associated literature there is no possibility of using the symbolÂ V2subscriptğ‘‰2V_{2}; indeed, often the code words inÂ (6.2) are truncated by removing the first two symbols. To say this another way, the choice of vertical directions at levelÂ 111 is somewhat arbitrary, and consequently the divisor at infinity I2subscriptğ¼2I_{2} is not well-defined. Thus the stratification of a monster space is, with this viewpoint, slightly coarser than what we are using in this paper.

Our earliest studies of the monster (Semple) tower [6, 7, 8] were focused on deriving formulas in enumerative geometry for algebraic curves in the projective plane; thus we were concerned with orbits of the monster spaces under the action of the projective linear group PGLâ€‹(2)PGL2{\rm PGL}(2). In this context, one wants an even finer stratification, in which, at levelÂ 222, there are three sorts of points:

  1. 1)

    a general point of â„™2â€‹(2)superscriptâ„™22\mathbb{P}^{2}(2) represents the curvilinear data of a nondegenerate conic at aÂ point;

  2. 2)

    there is still a divisor at infinity, whose points represent the data of certain singular curves;

  3. 3)

    there is a second divisor whose points represents the data of lines, and this is a distinguished locus invariant under the action of the group.

From this viewpoint, there are three possible symbols for the second entry of a code word. In our cited works, the symbols were 00, âˆ’-, and âˆ\infty; to pass to the code word of the present paper, replace 00 or âˆ’- by Rğ‘…R, and replace âˆ\infty by V2subscriptğ‘‰2V_{2}. In this finer stratification, there are eight strata at levelÂ 333, each of which happens to be a PGLâ€‹(2)PGL2{\rm PGL}(2)-orbit, as enumerated in [7, TheoremÂ 2], rather than the five strata listed in ExampleÂ 6.1 above or the two strata of the differential-geometric theory.

7 Speculations about other singularities

What should one expect if one carries out a similar analysis for a different sort of singular curveÂ Cğ¶C on a surface? If one prolongs the curve by itself, without reference to any family, one obtains its strict prolongation; for xâ€‹y=tğ‘¥ğ‘¦ğ‘¡xy=t that is simply the pair of end twigs. If one creates aÂ one-dimensional family in whichÂ Cğ¶C is the central member and all other members are nonsingular (aÂ smoothing family), one expects that the construction of this paper will yield three sorts of structures:

  1. 1)

    a configuration of curves, consisting of the strict prolongation together with prolongations of certain vertical curves;

  2. 2)

    a one-dimensional cycle obtained by assigning an appropriate multiplicity to each curve in the configuration;

  3. 3)

    a scheme whose fundamental class is this cycle.

The authors of [15] consider a locally irreducible curve, e.g., the Ansubscriptğ´ğ‘›A_{n} singularity defined by y2=xn+1superscriptğ‘¦2superscriptğ‘¥ğ‘›1y^{2}=x^{n+1}, and define a configuration of curves of the type just described. Their analysis shows that their configuration matches the configuration one obtains by the standard process of embedded resolution by point blowups, with the prolongations of vertical curves naturally matching up with the exceptional divisors of the standard process. (See [12, ChapterÂ 1] for an account of embedded resolution of curve singularities.) We think that the same configuration will emerge via prolongation of any smoothing family.

Embedded resolution produces even more: it associates a multiplicity to each exceptional divisor, and thus defines a cycle (in fact a divisor, since the entire configuration lies on aÂ surface). Here again we speculate that the prolongation of any smoothing family will yield the same multiplicities, i.e., that the same cycle will emerge, no matter which smoothing family is used.

As for scheme structure, one should note that the versal deformation space is typically of higher dimension; for example, the versal deformation of the Ansubscriptğ´ğ‘›A_{n} singularity consists of all curves

y2=xn+1+tnâ€‹xn+tnâˆ’1â€‹xnâˆ’1+â‹¯+t1â€‹x+t0.superscriptğ‘¦2superscriptğ‘¥ğ‘›1subscriptğ‘¡ğ‘›superscriptğ‘¥ğ‘›subscriptğ‘¡ğ‘›1superscriptğ‘¥ğ‘›1â‹¯subscriptğ‘¡1ğ‘¥subscriptğ‘¡0\displaystyle y^{2}=x^{n+1}+t_{n}x^{n}+t_{n-1}x^{n-1}+\cdots+t_{1}x+t_{0}.

One can obtain many different one-dimensional smoothing families by taking various curves within the base of the versal deformation. Here we anticipate that one can obtain many different limiting scheme structures on the central fiber, which reflect, in some fashion, the various directions of approach on the base. We hope to pursue these speculations further.
